knowledge_graph.title: Opossum
knowledge_graph.description: Opossums are members of the marsupial order Didelphimorphia endemic to the Americas. The largest order of marsupials in the Western Hemisphere, it comprises 126 species in 18 genera.

related_questions.question: What is difference between possum and opossum?
related_questions.snippet: Opossums are marsupials native to the Americas. They are characterized by white faces and sharp teeth. Possums are marsupials native to Australia and some neighboring countries. They are characterized by prehensile tails.
related_questions.title: Possum vs. Opossum – The Correct Way to Use Each | Confusing Words

related_questions.question: Can possums spread disease to humans?
related_questions.snippet: While they may carry diseases like leptospirosis or coccidiosis, transmission to humans is rare. In resume, yes, they carry some important diseases, but the transmission to humans is unlikely to happen. Likewise, at Critter Stop, as an expert opossum removal company, we recommend avoiding contact with these animals.

related_questions.question: Are possums related to rats?
related_questions.snippet: Although they are often described as “large rats”, opossums (Didelphis virginiana) are actually marsupials (relative of the kangaroo). They are the only marsupial in North America. They have a white face that is similar to a rat's, with a long, narrow, and pointed snout and they have rounded ears.

related_questions.question: Are possums a threat?
related_questions.snippet: If there is an opossum in your backyard, don't worry. They aren't a threat and more than likely will be moving on in a short while. The best way to keep them from visiting is to have tight-fitting lids on garbage cans and not to leave any pet food outside overnight.
